{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011hoJ58ssw5cro2Md4MCsL5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of:\n\n1. The feedback from iteration 27 (4 failure patterns, 11 cases total)\n2. The current implementation (~1500 lines of complex heuristic + embedding scoring)\n3. The history of iterations (steady improvement, real files at 100%, generated files plateauing)\n\nLet me now analyze the core problems and write the improvement plan.\n\nKey observations:\n- The code is already ~1500 lines of intricate heuristic logic\n- Each iteration adds more special cases and the complexity is growing\n- The 4 remaining failure patterns are:\n  1. OCR digit-for-letter corruption on title line (5 cases) - the extractor rejects corrupted titles\n  2. Category/section header precedes title (3 cases) - after skipping header, picks wrong line\n  3. Multi-line split title (1 case) - doesn't merge continuation lines\n  4. Previous-page content before title (2 cases) - picks wrong title from spillover\n\nThe fundamental issue is that `isLikelyGarbled` and the hard filters reject OCR-corrupted title lines, and then the fallback logic isn't robust enough to find the right line. Looking at the specific failure mechanisms, the OCR corruption pattern shows how the extractor rejects valid titles that contain digit substitutions, leaving it unable to recover when the fallback doesn't work.\n\nThe real problem is that `repairOcrText` only fixes words already in the food dictionary, so if \"braised\" isn't indexed, `Bra1sed` stays corrupted and gets flagged by `isLikelyGarbled` or fails the embedding score check since the mangled text doesn't embed well. at `isLikelyGarbled` more carefully - it checks vowel ratio, mixed case transitions, etc. A word like \"Bra1sed\" wouldn't trigger most of these. But the \"garbled word\" check at the end: `words.some(w => /^[a-z]/.test(w) && w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 && ...)` - this checks for short lowercase words. \"Bra1sed\" starts with uppercase so wouldn't hit that.\n\nActually the key issue might be more subtle. Let me re-read the feedback: \"The extractor either returns empty or returns a later line.\" So the corrupted title IS being generated as a candidate (passes hard filters), but its embedding score is low because MiniLM doesn't understand \"Bra1sed\" well, so it gets a low rawScore and loses to other candidates or falls below threshold.\n\nFor Pattern 2, the section header `FISH & SEAFOOD` gets correctly filtered since it's in SECTION_LABELS, but then the extractor picks the subtitle or description instead of the actual title. The first-after-preamble bonus should help, but the description might just have a higher embedding score than the title itself.\n\nFor Pattern 3 with the multi-line title, the caps coalescing logic isn't handling this case properly. \"LEMON HERB RO45TED\" followed by \"VEGETABLES\" - the second line is in CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS, and the coalescing code has a special case that allows category labels as continuation when the merged word count is at least 2. && wordCount(merged) <= 4`. So \"LEMON HERB RO45TED\" has 3 words, and \"VEGETABLES\" is a category label... it should work? Unless \"RO45TED\" prevents all-caps detection because of the digit. Actually `isAllCaps(\"LEMON HERB RO45TED\")` checks `letters = text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\")` → \"LEMONHERBROSTED\" which is all uppercase, so it returns true. Hmm.\n\nWait, let me re-read: the feedback says the extractor returned \"LEMON HERB ROASTED\" (just the first line). So it DID extract the first line but didn't merge the second. This means the caps coalescing is either not merging them, or they got merged but the shorter single version scored higher.\n\nActually, `repairOcrText` would turn \"RO45TED\" → \"ROASTED\" (if in dictionary), and the single-line \"LEMON HERB ROASTED\" passes hard filters and gets a good score. The 2-line join \"LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES\" would also be a candidate. But then dedup: \"LEMON HERB ROASTED\" is a substring of \"LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES\", so the shorter one wins (the dedup rule keeps shorter). And the compound title protection only applies for \" + \", \" : \", \" & \" separators.\n\nSo the fix for Pattern 3 is: when the longer candidate is a 2-line join and the shorter is its prefix, AND the appended word is a food-related word (from CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS or food dictionary), prefer the longer form. This is a de\n\ndup rule issue.\n\nFor Pattern 4: Previous-page spillover content. The `findBurstEnd` function has overflow marker detection, but the feedback says it \"picks a different recipe's title\" or \"an instruction line.\" This suggests the spillover detection isn't catching the specific patterns in these test cases.\n\nOK, let me now think about what the improvement plan should look like. The fundamental question is: should we keep iterating on the current approach, or rethink it?\n\nThe current approach is already very complex (1500 lines). Each pattern fix risks regressions elsewhere. But the remaining failures are all on generated (synthetic) files, not real ones. And the patterns are fairly clear.\n\nI think the right approach is targeted fixes for each pattern, but with some structural improvement to reduce the chance of regression:\n\n1. **OCR corruption tolerance**: Before hard-filtering, apply aggressive OCR repair (not just dictionary-\n\nSo the real issue with Pattern 3 is the dedup logic—when a longer candidate is a 2-line join and the shorter one is its prefix, I should prefer the longer form if the appended word is food-related. For Pattern 4, the spillover detection in `findBurstEnd` isn't catching the specific patterns where it picks up a different recipe's title or instruction line. The current approach is already complex at 1500 lines, and each fix risks breaking something else, but since the failures are only on synthetic test files and the patterns are clear, I think targeted fixes with some structural improvements to prevent regressions make sense—starting with more aggressive OCR repair before applying hard filters.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4991,"cache_read_input_tokens":57726,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4991},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"67c804db-4061-40f8-823f-56265230248d","uuid":"da793bd0-91bd-43ed-acca-de2e0b77c78b"}
